
"Where does ChatGPT fit in the AI hierarchy?"

A strong answer is:

"ChatGPT is a Generative AI application powered by a Large Language Model (LLM). 
The LLM is built using Deep Learning, which is a subset of Machine Learning, 
and Machine Learning itself is a subset of Artificial Intelligence.
ChatGPT mainly works on Natural Language Processing tasks such as understanding and generating human language."

| Traditional Programming             | Rule-Based AI                                | Machine Learning                          |
| ----------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Programmer writes business logic    | Experts provide domain knowledge as rules    | Model learns patterns from data           |
| Uses `if`, `else`, loops, functions | Uses a knowledge base + inference engine     | Uses algorithms trained on data           |
| No reasoning                        | Reasons using expert knowledge               | Learns and improves from examples         |
| No learning                         | No learning                                  | Learns from data                          |
| Example: ATM, Shopping Cart         | Medical diagnosis, Legal advice, Tax systems | Spam detection, Face recognition, ChatGPT |


One small correction to keep in mind

People sometimes casually say "rule-based AI = lots of if-else statements." That's an oversimplification. The important difference is purpose and architecture:

In traditional programming, rules implement application/business logic.
In rule-based AI, rules represent expert knowledge stored in a knowledge base, and an inference engine uses those rules to reason and reach conclusions.

That's why rule-based AI was considered an early form of AI, even though it didn't learn from data the way modern AI systems do.






